formattedAddress: 621 N Palm Canyon Dr (btwn Tamarisk & Alejo)

contact.facebookName: Rip Current Brewing in North Park
Mike Hess Brewing Company North Park

venue.name: Stone Brewing World Bistro & Gardens Liberty Station

contact.facebookName: Stone Brewing World Bistro & Gardens - Liberty Station

tip.text: Great selection of craft beer on tap and flatbread pizza

formattedAddress: 383 Market St Bldg D (at Sampson St)

contact.facebookName: The Plank Pizza Co. Beer Parlor

venue.name: The Plank Pizza Co. Beer Parlor

tip.text: Salvation is reaching unprecedented levels of hype for their burger in Midtown East and with April Bloomfield's credentials from Spotted Pig and Breslin, it must be good. The burger is good

venue.name: C.H. Evans Brewing Co. at the Albany Pump Station

formattedAddress: 263 rue Saint-Viateur Ouest (entre Jeanne-Mance & du Parc)

tip.text: Flex Mussels, an import to NYC from PEI (that’s Prince Edward Island in Canada, where the good mussels are from), has some of the best mussels in the city. For dinner or Sunday brunch, get a bucket
Nestled in a vaulted stone chapel of the church above, Bluestone serves a strong coffee and brunch. The ambience makes you want to repent for your sins, but you won’t regret the brew.
While the food here is pretty solid, especially pasta and sandwiches, the service and clientele was so awful on a recent visit that it will be my last time there.

Court Street has some of the tastiest sandwiches in the city all in what looks like a corner grocery store. In front, there are shelves of snacks and drinks from around the world including interesting

formattedAddress: 485 Court St (btwn Nelson and Huntington St)

tip.text: Awesome brewery with a cozy industrial feel and tons of beer to choose from. They have a selection of about a half dozen of their own beers on tap plus a selection of “friend” breweries they also have
A pretty standard bar with a California theme and a decent selection of craft beer on tap. The room in the back is nice for relaxing on big comfy couches and a projector for sports.

location.crossStreet: btwn St. Marks Pl & Bergen St
formattedAddress: 82 4th Ave (btwn St. Marks Pl & Bergen St)

tip.text: For what looks like the least unique and interesting spot in Gotham Market, only because of the trendy and upscale ramen, tapas, and charcuterie joints nearby, Genuine, more of a roadside joint
Everyman is a tiny coffee shop with good coffee, but the location makes it painful to enjoy. The space is shared with a theater and though we were unlucky to go in right as the show was lining up
Lion’s beer store, another entry in the beer store / bar venues in the city pulls this dynamic off pretty well. Focusing mostly on Belgian and Belgian style beer, including most of the trappists
Cheeky has been described as the best sandwiches in NYC, and though they don’t necessarily live up to that high bar, they are quite good. Service is pleasant though a little slow, but at least fresh
Goa Taco now has a brick and mortar store after seeing good success as a pop up in various markets throughout the city. The paratha bread taco shells are perfect for the toppings, nice and big, thick

formattedAddress: 79 Delancey St (btwn Allen St & Orchard St)

tip.text: Park Ave Tavern was a pleasant surprise in an area not known for great restaurants. The food isn’t amazing or particularly memorable, but it is solid and the space is very cozy. Service wasn’t great
Though you don’t get to customize your burrito here like other fast casual spots, the salsa bar options are a nice substitute here and the menu is big enough to appeal to many tastes. There are wings
Hyde Park Brewing is an awesome surprise brewpub in an unassuming spot right off the main road in Hyde Park. The interior is what a modern brew pub should be, complete with brewing tanks
Lombardi’s claims to have invented the NYC pizza style, and they certainly do have the feel of a long lived New York institution. The restaurant is traditional pizza joint through and through

contact.facebookName: The burger joint at the Parker Meridien

formattedAddress: Ramapo Valley Rd (US-202) (btwn Darlington Ave & Emma Ct)

contact.facebookName: New York - New Jersey Trail Conference

formattedAddress: 200 E 3rd St (btwn Ave A & Ave B)

tip.text: Luckily the excellent La Colombe has a flagship store on the way back to the East Side. At La Columbe, a massive temple to the majestic coffee bean, complete with marble decor and massive pillars

The newest entry to the Fuku empire (an empire so large and mighty now that it is very easy to confuse restaurants and enter the noodle bar instead of Fuku accidentally), Fuku opened to constant lines

formattedAddress: 96 Saint Marks Pl (btwn 1st Ave & Avenue A)

tip.text: Hometown has recently earned a reputation for being the best BBQ in the city, and it is pretty immediately obvious why. It is incredibly authentic to Texas BBQ standards, particularly Austin
NJPAC hosted a talk by Neil Degrasse Tyson who talked about physics in movies. The hall definitely feels world class with great architecture and very good acoustics. It was very easy to hear and see
Cozy little craft beer spot. It's becoming thankfully easier to find bars with decent craft beer menus in New York. Proletariat doesn't have a good list, it has a great one. You'll find unique beer

formattedAddress: 102 Saint Marks Pl (btwn 1st Ave & Avenue A)

tip.text: Awesome low key bar that sells fantastic tacos. It's hard to say if it is a bar or restaurant from the setup. There are no reservations and no waiters so just grab a table and order at the bar.
Birch risks feeling pretentious with a tiny area and fairly high prices, but the friendly staff makes it feel more human. There are only three small tables inside and some room at the bar
When we couldn’t find an open table at any of the nearby restaurants, London Grill’s big dinning room had room. The bar area which is decent sized with about 4 high tops tables and a bunch of seating
Rai Rai recently reopened after a fire shuttered the original. The outside doesn’t look like much sit is in a strip mall amongst many other nondescript strip malls. Inside though, it’s fairly classy
The inside is a bit tight but it actually goes way further back that you'd expect so except when there is a huge abnormal crowd, like during Web Summit, there is ample space. The outside is great
A beautiful architectural statement in Belfast, Queen’s is worth a visit just to explore the grounds. The botanic gardens are also right next door and make for a nice quick stroll.
Contra, a New American style restaurant that features a tasting menu only menu, is pretty solid. The service was a little lacking in a few areas, from being a bit hostile about one of our party
RDS hosts the annual Web Summit, and in 2015 hosted 46,000 attendees. The space is enormous and expansive, covering two major buildings with a walk between them. Having a 10 minute or so walk
For an amazing unforgettable culinary experience in the city center, Pig’s Ear is definitely at the top of the list. The entire experience from beginning to end is phenomenal. The atmosphere is great
Dublin’s culinary scene is probably not well known for good Japanese and sushi, but Yammamori is slowly working to change that perception. Once you enter the basement, you are transported from Dublin

Beautiful and historic, the castle should be near the top of anyone’s list for touring Dublin city. The architecture is astounding and very imposing. Make sure to explore the courtyard for more modern

Blaze, the newest in Chipotle or Subway style build your own food chain focuses on pizza and does a pretty good job. Pizza is cooked in about 3 minutes which is staggering considering how many topping
Porterhouse is a great showroom for the multitudes of beer produced by the brewer of the same name. There are about a dozen various beers on tap from the brewer plus a few more guest taps
Situated in an old bank (hence the name), the Bank is a great restaurant with live music and drinks. You’re not likely to forget you are in an old bank with the vaulted ceiling and awesome skylight

The Ha’penny bridge crosses the river and allows pedestrian access between north and south sides. The name apparently comes from the toll charged (half a penny) when opened as it replaced several ferr

The Gresham Hotel is an institution in Dublin, so much so that you never need to worry about getting lost as everyone in town knows it. The location is great for touring Dublin as most sights are clos
Looking for a little taste of the grand ole days with some nice cocktails? Rita's ha a great atmosphere with big comfy couches and even a fireplace near the huge bar. Drinks are crafted not made
Amazing Michelin star rated restaurant and only the second in Belfast. Get the full tasting menu with wine pairings for the best experience. Venison was an incredible dish and cheese is phenominal
I might actually like this place if it weren't for the crowd. On a Friday night, Flatiron Hall is bro central and was nearly intolerable. The decor definitely catered to the crowd with lots of wood

contact.facebookName: Flatiron Hall Restaurant and Beer Cellar

tip.text: Don't expect a major league stadium experience, and you won't be disappointed. The newly built PPL Center is now in its second season but still feels new. The amenities aren't immensely impressive
With some more time to solidify itself, Bell Hall could become the best option for pre-gaming PPL Center events. For now though, they have some potential but need to realize it. Decent beer list

Good brewery but not the best in LIC. The beer project is a new entry to the ever increasingly popular beer crawl in LIC and it feels a bit like they grew too fast. The space is huge but not many seat
Paulie Gee's is a solid option for good pizza in Brooklyn, but I think there are better options. It didn't compare to Roberta's in Bushwick or Marta in Manhattan, but was still pretty good pizza

formattedAddress: 60 Greenpoint Ave (btwn Franklin St & West St)

tip.text: Weyerbacher is not afraid to make some bold beer. Their most popular brews are high IBU IPAs and very malty brews. This means you can probably find something for anyone here though. The space is great
Bombay Pizza is a unique and tasty option for pizza in Houston. The pizza has an indian food theme with toppings like chicken tikka and saag paneer. The service is super friendly and pretty quick
Siphon is a very trendy coffee shop that can feel a little pretentious, but the coffee is solid and the atmosphere is great. The siphon coffee is very interesting and looks like a chemistry set

Let's get this out of the way first, Portland Lobster Company is definitely a touristy spot, but beyond that, there is some good food and fun times to be had here. The deck is huge and overlooks water
Duckfat, named for the duck fat that they fry the fries in, is exceptional for both said fries (frites) and the sandwiches. The line gets crazy long in the summer, so either get in early, be prepared
Portland Flea-for-All is a wonderland of antiques and yard sale type stuff. It expands to three floors of various stuff for every desire. They have video game posters, antique chairs, military water
Sebago is located in what feels like (probably because it is) the bottom of a hotel. the beer is awesome however, and even though the atmosphere is a bit clinical and hotel bar feeling, it is nice

Spring Point Lighthouse is another fairly small lighthouse like Bug Point, a short drive from Portland. The parking lot is tiny and often full so you may be in for a walk. The Lighthouse can be walked
Din Tai Fung is super popular for dumplings for good reason. It's not uncommon to see big crowds waiting outside for dinner because the dumplings are worth the wait. Takeout was a little slow

contact.facebookName: Din Tai Fung University Village 鼎泰豐

tip.text: Hi Spot is a good solid breakfast spot where nothing was incredible, but everything was pretty good. The coffee is good, but pretty much what you'd expect at a dinner. The Sammy Sue sandwich was good
Frelard (named because it is between Freemont and Ballard, get it?) is a nice space that will feel very familiar to the Ballard or Freemont crowd with a large open garden seating area

Hitchcock is a great place for the island, but could have been better. This is definitely still a place I'd bring friends or family to for special occasions when visiting the island, but could be bett
Great park along the water on Bainbridge Island. Though it's at the opposite end of the the island from the ferry, it's a pretty quick car drive. The park goes along the beach and has some nice views
The Holy Donut is a destination for donut lovers the world over. The donuts here are in high enough demand that they are nearly always fresh baked and warm. They are somehow made from potato
Gorgeous Gelato has some amazing Gelato in the touristy area of downtown Portland. This shop is no tourist trap though. The gelato is excellent and they have many flavors.
Fort Allen Park is a nice stretch of a park along the water along the old narrow gauge rail lines. The path is well maintained and great for running, walking, or cycling. As you round the promontory
When Arrogant Swine announced they'd be hosting the famous Danish brewer from Mikkeller, we had to go. The space is very nice with a ton of outdoor seating though the neighborhood is still on the up.
Speckled Ax would do great in Brooklyn as well. The staff is great at making a tasty cup, but will make you feel like a tiny human being doing so. The interior is tiny
Baxter woods is a fairly unique forested park boxed between residential streets. You have to park on one of the nearby streets to enter. However, you quickly forget how close to houses you are

location.crossStreet: Between Hartley St. and Pershing St.
formattedAddress: 850 Forest Ave (Between Hartley St. and Pershing St.)
600 Cape May St (at Frank E Rodgers Blvd.)

tip.text: Definitely an old timers joint that is an institution in the city. Very similar to Minetta in that you would fully expect patrons to have been coming here every day for thirty years. Burger was just k
Cool little coffee shop with tons of light and a little steampunk vibe. The service was super slow, but the drinks good. The Japanese cold brew was delicious and not at all bitter.
Red Bull arena is a great place to see a soccer game. Parking is a bit confusing and painful going in as traffic is restricted, but we got out pretty quick. It's also right next to the path train.

formattedAddress: 600 Cape May St (at Frank E Rodgers Blvd.)

tip.text: Donut Plant is the place to go for an enormous and tasty donut. They've been baking here for ever and apparently invented every type of donut if the signs on the walls are to be believed. Go square
The hype is real, Babu Ji may just be my new go to Indian place. First impressions matter, and my first impression was of a taxidermy peacock perched above a self serve beer fridge with over 30 types
I'll be spending the rest of my life, living in a Filipino food paradise. Maharika introduced me to the world of Filipino food, and I'll never turn back after the brunch. The ambiance is just ok
Danny Meyers's pizza joint is a bit of a surprise after patronizing his most famous, Shake Shack. There is no A and B line here, but a nicely decorated fairly upscale but inviting feeling restaurant

formattedAddress: 29 E 29th St (btwn Madison & Park Ave S)

tip.text: A nice rooftop bar and beer garden where you will extremely thankful to get off the cramped and exceptionally slow elevator. This area of the city seems to attract a good number of Europeans

Very cool Japanese style coffee shop that feels more like the inside of a train car than a normal coffee shop. You can either order to go or sit at the long bar with your drink. Great pour over coffee

An awesome space for tons of sculptures, especially the life like ones. Tickets are a little steep at $15 a person and you can explore pretty much the whole thing in 2 hours at a fairly leisurely walk

West End Hall is the newest beer hall on the Upper West Side and enters the market with a good selection of brew and some pretty good food. The staff was ok, but very slow and forgot to take our order
Azur is one of the most unique and delicious restaurants in Dubrovnik, a town otherwise full of touristy seafood spots. The menu is Malaysian Croatian fusion, but it's mostly Croatian favorites
Scorpio is a restaurant pretty exclusively targeting tourists. Located in the main town square, it is predominantly patronized by the cruise ship crowd. Sadly food is targeted toward them as well
The old city and walls of Kotor are beautiful and a wonderful place to explore. Sadly, the city hasn't seemed to have embraced the new tourism coming there as there is still a good amount of grafitti

St. Nikola is one of the more interesting churches in Kotor due to the Orthodox decor. Pictures aren't strictly allowed. The incense and gold adorned decor and icons create a very interesting atmosphe
Lokanda sits right on the harbor of Dubrovnik's old town and stretches pretty far around. This is definitely a place for tourists as you are right where the ships let off, but the seafood is good

The city walls are amazing and offer some great views of Dubrovnik and the water. You can wander around them endlessly if you don't get sick of the crowds of tourists. You can enter either at the Pile
We checked out Orhan at the suggestion of a local for excellent traditional seafood in Dubrovnik. It is a bit off the beaten path, as you have to leave the old city and meander through the alleys
Conte is a great restaurant for food or drinks in the historical town of Perast. You can dine on the water overlooking the majestical bay almost right under the Venetian style tower. Service was slow
If it weren't for the amazing atmosphere and staff at Luna, the sister restaurant down the street, Giaxa would have been the best restaurant we visited in Croatia. Amazing seafood and service
One of the few sand beaches we found in Croatia, that seems to be the main draw. The view is nice, but not as grand as other spots in the city. The area is a bit run down and a bit dirty
There are no shortage of bars and caffes along the harbor in Stari Grad, and Lampedusa fits in well. Their umbrellas seemed slightly larger and cooler than some of the others. Good wifi decent beer
Villa Apolon was one of the highlights of our trip to Croatia. The staff was incredibly warm and welcoming from check in to check out including the wait staff, concierge, and even owner.
Marjan is the perfect place to escape from the noise and chaos of the touristy old town Split. The parks and beaches are a short walk from town, but not many tourists make it, so it is fairly calm
Hvaranin sticks out in Split as it doesn't try to stick out. Unlike the flashy restaurants along the water, Hvaranin is just outside the main touristy area, so manages to feel a bit more authentic.
The interior of the Cathedral isn't incredibly interesting and is smaller than you'd think. The bell tower is a must do in the city and offers amazing views of the old town, palace, and harbor.

venue.name: Cathedral of St. Domnius (Katedrala Sv. Duje)

tip.text: A must visit fortress that even if it weren't for Game of Thrones would be worth the visit. The view is amazing. You can get in for just a few kuna and they clearly haven't figured out the GoT merch
It's hard to describe in words how beautiful this is. The lakes are seemingly endless with perfectly clear water, beautiful green vegetation, wildlife, and stunning waterfalls. It gets very busy

venue.name: Plitvice Lakes National Park (Plitvička Jezera National Park)

tip.text: Fantastic place to stay, I just wish we had stayed longer. The fairly new apartments are very close to the lakes and make for a great staging point for exploring as well as for traveling
In an area known for pretty average, touristy food, this is among the best. The menu is meat heavy with a few other choices. The pizzas are probably the most recommended and the one with cream cheese
A must visit landmark in Zagreb that is the unofficial symbol of the city. The mosaic roof with tiles displaying the town crest are beautiful and unique. The square is also pretty with government
Good coffee at an outdoor sidewalk cafe. The people watching here is great. Coffee is ok, a step above instant. Service was very slow. Nice for a stop before exploring town.
An amazing hotel and resort where you can escape the crowds and feel like a celebrity. We were lucky and got a great rate here, otherwise you'll pay dearly in the summer. Staff could improve

formattedAddress: 29 E 29th St (btwn Madison & Park Ave S)

tip.text: Amazing once in a lifetime food. The seafood, veal, and lamb were all excellent and the menu is interesting but not too adventurous. Wine selection is a literal book. Amazing service and very romantic
Konobo Mondo is well known for its truffles and for good reason. In the world capital of truffles of Istria, it's hard to find a restaurant that doesn't serve them. Still, a bit touristy but not trap
I can never get enough of dragons in bridges, and this bridge has not one but four!  The dragon was added when the bridge was built and became the symbol of the city. Very pretty area
